Virtual Dutch Flashcards in R.

A Shiny application supporting words and verbs declination memorization.

Jacek Pardyak

2019-03-23

Introduction

When I started learning Dutch I couldn’t find R project which will support my vocabulary memorization. So I started myself virtual flashcards1 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flashcard project in Shiny. What is absurd, my goal is I don’t need them any more in a nearly future. Maybe someone else vindt het leuk.

The data

There are two data sets:

  1. List of Dutch words with English translation,

Vocabulary loosely covers material from this Handbook2 De opmaat, Naar NT2-niveau A2, Maud Beersmans, Wim Tersteeg and is stored in JSON files. There are also words I found interesting to me.

  1. List of irregular Dutch verbs with conjugation forms.

The list is a compilation of above mentioned book and Handbook3 Niderlandzki, Gramatyka z ćwiczeniami, Katarzyna Wiercińska

I have chosen JSON file format in favour of CSV because one word can have more then one translation (or conjugation form) or can appear in several Themas in a different context and meaning. List data structure is very natural to store that kind of data. The first dataset is a data frame with lists, the second is data frame of nested data frames.

The structure of woordenlijst.json is as follows:

The script

Script of my Shiny application is stored in two files available from this Repository4 https://github.com/JacekPardyak/FC:

  1. ui.R

  2. server.R

This is the header of ui.R file:

Shortly about the R libraries:

  • shiny5 https://shiny.rstudio.com/ is a general framework for building web applications,

  • shinydashboard6 https://rstudio.github.io/shinydashboard/ turns Shiny applications into cool dashboards,

  • jsonlite7 https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/jsonlite/ is used to process JSON files,

  • dt8 https://rstudio.github.io/DT/ is used to edit table directly in the dashboard.

The application

As of 2019-03-23 my application supports:

  1. Memorization of the Dutch words,

  2. Learning forms of irregular Dutch verbs.

The usage is straightforward.

Further work
